Linear regression basics

We start by setting up the model and estimating it. This assumes that the data are clean and and that there are no other issues with the data.

regModel <- lm(WAGE ~ EDUCATION + EXPERIENCE, data = mynewdf)

Regression diagnostics

plot(regModel)

  • Plot #1: (residuals vs.fitted values) is a scatterplot between residuals and predicted values. It should look more or less random. This is more or less what what we see here, with the exception of a single outlier in the top center.

  • Plot #2: The second plot (normal Q-Q) is a normal probability plot.It should give a straight line if the errors are distributed normally, but point 171 and a few others force it to deviate from the straight line.

  • Plot #3: The third plot (Scale-Location), similar to the the first lot, should look random. No patterns.Ours hasan upward slope.

  • Plot #4: The last plot (Cooks distance) tells us which points have the greatest influence on the regression (leverage points). We see that points 171, 169, and 108 have a lot of influence on the model.

Why do we take a log transform?

Typically three reasons (there could be more)

  • If your residuals arent normally distributed (as was the case here) then taking the logarithm of a skewed variable could improve fit by changing the scale and making the variable closer to a normally distributed one.

  • For purposes of interpretation or rather convenience of interpretation

    • Y and X a one unit increase in X would lead to a \(\beta\) increase/decrease in Y
    • Log Y and Log X a 1% increase in X would lead to a \(\beta\) % increase/decrease in Y
    • Log Y and X a one unit increase in X would lead to a \(\beta\) ???100 % increase/decrease in Y
    • Y and Log X a 1% increase in X would lead to a \(\beta\) /100 increase/decrease in Y

  • There could be a theoretical reason. Some models are multiplicative and consequently nonlinear. Taking the log allows these models to be estimated by linear regression. These models include the Cobb-Douglas production function in economics and the Mincer Equation in education.

  • One reason you wouldnt use log tramsforms is to remove outliers

Looks like there is a case to be made for multicollinearity. We check multicollinearity using VIFs

Variance inflation factor

  • The variance inflation factor (VIF) provides a measure of how much the variance is inflated.
  • Variance of what?
  • We know that the standard errors (and, therefore the variances) of the estimated regression coefficients are inflated when multicollinearity exists.
  • So, the VIF for the estimated coefficient bk (denoted VIFk) is the factor by which the variance is inflated.
vif(fitAll)

What to do?

There are several ways to deal with multicollinearity including using prinicipal components for regression, ridge Regression, or Stepwise Regression.

  • We will use the VIF scores to delete the variable with the highest VIF EXPERIENCE
  • Usually, variables with VIF scores > 10 need to be investigated

Criteria

  • Cp An underspecified model is a model in which important predictors are missing. Therefore, an underspecified model yields biased regression coefficients and biased predictions of the response. Mallows Cp-statistic estimates the size of the bias that is introduced into the predicted responses by having an underspecified model.
  • AIC is a number that is helpful for comparing models as it includes measures of both how well the model fits the data and how complex the model is. Lower is better.
  • Bayes information criterion (BIC), also known as Schwartz information criterion (SIC). SBIC penalizes model complexity more heavily.
  • Schwarz (1978) developed a model selection criterion that was derived from a Bayesian modification of the AIC criterion. Schwarz Bayesian Criteria (SBC) is a function of the number of observations n, the SSE, and the number of independent variables k ??? p + 1 where k includes the intercept.
